                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d310">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé d’Affaires in China</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MJVA1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-19T18:00:00-05:00">
                        <hi rend="italic">August 19, 1914, 6 p.m.</hi>
                    </date>
                </dateline>
                <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                <p>Your telegram of August 19, 5 p.m. The American Government has not said that it
                    regards the Japanese promise to restore Kiaochow to China as satisfactory, but
                    in accordance with its attitude of strict neutrality the American Government has
                    refrained from expressing any opinion upon the merits of the question.
                    Communications to and from the Department relating to this matter are being
                    repeated to you. You will be kept informed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
